        "conclusion": {
            "id": "conclusion",
            "title": "Conclusion",
            "isApplicable": true,
            "content": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "In this experiment, the implementation of a full subtractor on the FPGA board was successfully completed. Both software simulation and hardware implementation were performed and verified against the respective truth table. Different cases that produce similar output combinations were identified. The experiment demonstrates that the Difference output expression is identical to that of the full adder Sum, while the Borrow expression uses the complement of the minuend A — highlighting the structural relationship between addition and subtraction in combinational arithmetic circuits."
                }
            ]
        },
        "postLab": {
            "id": "postLab",
            "title": "Post-Lab / Viva Voce",
            "isApplicable": true,
            "content": [
                {
                    "type": "list",
                    "style": "ordered",
                    "items": [
                        "**Q:** What is the difference between a half subtractor and a full subtractor?\n**A:** Half subtractor handles 2 inputs (A, B) and no borrow-in. Full subtractor handles 3 inputs (A, B, Bin) to support multi-bit cascading.",
                        "**Q:** Why is the Difference expression in a full subtractor identical to the Sum expression in a full adder?\n**A:** Both use XOR logic (odd parity) for the result bit. The difference lies only in the carry/borrow generation logic.",
                        "**Q:** When does Borrow-out become high?\n**A:** When Minuend < Subtrahend (effectively). Boolean: `Bout = (~A&B) | (B&Bin) | (Bin&~A)`.",
                        "**Q:** How is subtraction typically done in processors?\n**A:** Using 2's complement addition. A - B is equal to A + (~B + 1). This allows the same Adder hardware to perform subtraction.",
                        "**Q:** Comparison of Adder vs Subtractor Truth Tables?\n**A:** Sum and Difference columns are identical. Carry and Borrow columns differ based on the majority vs borrowing logic."
                    ]
                }
            ]
        },
